Wednesday Jan. 23, 1929

Spend the afternoon in the Field Museum. Checked the rattlers fairly well. Met Simms, Osgood and some others.

Friday Jan. 25, 1929

Spent the day after 10am in the USNM. Met Dr. Stegneger and Miss. Cochran. Also Remington Kellogg, A Wright and Mrs. Wright (of Cornell) and Fowler of the Philadelphia Academy.
Worked on rattlers until 4:30. Got fairly well acquainted with available materials.

Monday Jan 28, 1929

Feb. Sunday 3, 1929

  • AMS 03/09/2014 08:15 AM
  • lwilliams 08/21/2011 10:44 AM
  • BPOC 11/23/2010 04:21 PM

Monday Feb. 4, 1929

Traveling through Arizona.
Winslow is an almost flat prairie. No rocks. Little brush. Looks like it would be good soil with water. Some distant escarpments and washes.
At Canyon Diablo it is still virtually bare. Quite level except for a few rocky gorges of which Canyon Diablo is an example.
At milepost 322 (and somewhat before) the Juniper? forest has begun. The land has become rolling and rocky.
At milepost 328 it is rough, hilly and rocky. Plenty of Junipers. This is Winona. Plenty of pines in the distance.
At Cosnino there are many big trees and a snowstorm has begun.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 08/21/2011 10:50 AM
  • BPOC 11/23/2010 04:21 PM

Thursday Feb.7, 1929

Went to meeting of the Herpetological Society of Calif in LA tonight. A talk on snakes by Bryan of Riverside.
He exhibited a queer Calif King. An even series of spots down the dorsal line from head to tail. Two quite even lines on each side. Mottled and striped below.

Tuesday Mar. 5, 1929

Recd today from Seavl two Boyles Kings, some lizards and 3 Hyla regilla from Mission Valley. All with localities designated. Recd from Ayres(??) a small gopher from Imperial Beach. Recd from Gander(??) 2 Aneides from Mission Valley and saw another alive.

One Boyles King San Diego contained a small gopher snake
One do San Diego Found under plaster
Lizards were 2 Utas and 1 skelly.

Notes:

lwilliams

Monday Mar. 11, 1929

Recd today via Ayres a small Arizona elegans occidentalis caught by A.L. Pickens at San Felipe. Caught under a rock. Contained a partly digested lizard and seemed to be a full grown Uta stans.

Drove to Los Angeles late in the afternoon starting at 4:05. A cool day; rained yesterday
Miles in the county 61.5
One young gopher at La Jolla DOR at the start of the Hog Canon grade.

Friday Mar. 15, 1929

Drove to El Cajon (out Broadway, back Cajon ave) thence to Escondido and back via Hodges Dam and Del Mar. Total 110 miles.
1 snake seen. Small gopher DOR at Santa Fe Ranch.

1929 Saturday 16, Mar.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/09/2014 08:27 AM
  • lwilliams 08/23/2011 10:54 AM
  • BPOC 11/23/2010 04:21 PM

Sunday Mar. 17, 1929

Today went 7 miles beyond the Narrows with family and the Uhlendorfs. Started at 10am, returned at 6:15. A cool cloudy day in town with high fog. On the desert clear with some wind. Not warm. Wend out via Broadway, La Mesa, Julian and Banner, returned same way except via Fletcher Hills and El Cajon Ave. 186 miles.
No snakes seen alive or dead. Hunted only one place - Yaqui Well - where we lunched, and there for a short time only.
No lizards were seen on the desert except a half dozen Utas. Got one at Yaqui Well. Caught two Hyla regilla in Yaqui Well but turned them loose again.

Saturday Mar. 30, 1929

Recd today a small Ensatina from Searl caught in Idyllwild Riverside Co.
This afternoon went to Corte Madera. A cold cloudy windy day 54.7 miles. Went via El Cajon Ave.
1 gopher Juv DOR at Alpine
1 do large do do
1 Trimorphodon large DOR at Old Viejas Grade towards bottom
This evening at Corte Madera the Hyla regilla were calling in the ponds.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 08/23/2011 11:53 AM
  • BPOC 11/23/2010 04:21 PM

Sunday Mar. 31, 1929

Walked up to the top of Corte Madera Mt in the morning. Saw Skellies and several half grown orcuttis. Xantusias negative. Saw 1 half grown skink. Caught 1 Batrachoseps under a log.
The nights are still quite cold.
the day while clear was cool
Nothing seen on return trip

Apr. Saturday 6, 1929

Today Walker brought in a small Batrachoseps from Bostonia.

Had planned to go out to Coyote Well this weekend with Weiss and Walker, but today was cold following several wet days so called it off.

Spent the weekend packing rattlers for shipment back to the institutions from which they were borrowed.

Material should be examined in following order:
A. scutulatus - confluentus investigation
1. Kansas 2. Harvard 3. AM.NH.
B. Tigris - mitchelli investigation

Material to be checked of small stunted almost white confluentus from South Eastern S.E Utah and South Western S.W. Colo.
A.M.N.H. 1
Michigan 1
Cal Acad 2
Field 2 (To be sent for).
U.C. 2 (On the edge - not as good).
Colorado 2 do. 1 is only a head.

Principal material still to be sent for.
U.S.N.M. Various and extensive
Field 2 Colo conflue and Hellers tigris
U.C. Camps Turtle Mt. Mitchell also various Northern Cal oreganus; new material from Lower Cal. and Nev..
Carnegie Collection from Pittsburgh promised by Netting
Stanford Collection.

Notes:

SPalmer

I'm sorry but I'm not sure what colo conflue and hellers tigris are.

SPalmer

I looked up Camp Turtle and Mt. Mitchell and I think Mt. Mitchell is in N. Carolina but not sure and I don't know where or what Camp Turtle is.

SPalmer

1929 Sunday 7, Apr.

Today I packed specimens for shipment and shipped to Michigan, Cornell, Kansas, Gloyd and Utah. this completes all shipments to be made at this time.

Also preserved specimens. Also got ready for book talk to fellows S.D.S.N.H. tomorrow.

Specimens still retained for entire checking or for further consideration as of this date are as follows

AMNH
Ortenburger Collection of atrox and scutulatus 1 or 2 other items including 1 S.E. Utah. A total of 39 snakes including 8 embryos.

Harvard
A misc. collection of about 13 snakes. Not touched yet. Checked and returned July 21st.

USNM
Entire Death Valley Expedition collection of tigris.

Colorado
2 confluentus from S.W. part of state.

Kansas
1 Remaining brood of New Mexico Conflu.

Michigan
1 Confluentus from S.E. Utah.

Bogert
Utah material ready to return. Returned in June

U. California
2 NE Ariz Tigris, all Cal. and Nevada Tigris, some Mitchelli and San Joaquin oreganus.

Cal. Acad.
2 Utah confluentus and 1 Arizona oreganus.

1929 Saturday 13, Apr.

Went out today to the Palm Canyon on the west side of Borego Valley. Weiss and Chuck had gone the day before. Took Phil in my car. Peckham, L.B. Jones, G.S. Myers and Cranzthor made up the party. Started at 1:10. Arrived at 5:30. Distance 100.2 miles. Went out by way of El Cajon Ave and Fletcher Hills. It was a cool and windy day. Cloudy. Quite cold at Julian. Picked up Myers at Julian.

First stop at Sentenac Canyon bridge. Myers got 1 Hyla of each species. I saw 2 Orcuttis under a rock.

In Borega Valley it was clear, cold and windy. Saw a piece of a Rhinocheilus caught in town of Borega. Very wide black rings with almost no red. Large size.

Hunted after supper until 9P.M. Myers saw one lizard but nothing else was seen. Wind had stopped (Weiss said it had blown strongly the previous night and all day) but it was quite cold. Ground was cold.

1 M. lateralis D.O.R., Med Shady Dell
1 R. lecontei D.O.R., L. Borega (see above)

  • SPalmer 02/12/2012 05:54 PM
  • BPOC 11/23/2010 04:21 PM

Apr. Sunday 14, 1929

This morning at 7:30 started up Palm Canyon. A fine clear warm day. Not hot. Little breeze. About 5 miles to the nearest Palms??. The Canyon is very rocky.

Collected the following:
Uta microscutata
Uta stansburiana
Uta mearnsi
Cnemidophorus tessellatus
Hyla arenicolor
Sauromalus obesus
Crotaphytus collaris
Xantusia henshawi

The microscutes were fairly plentiful up where the rocks were most plentiful and were on both light and dark rocks. Here they seemed to replace the Uta stans which was more plentiful further down the wash. Uta mearnsi was quite common. The whiptails and collared lizards were taken at the beginning of the wash. Hylas were plentiful on the boulders and in the water but not easy to catch. Both chucks were taken by myself under thick flakes. Xantusia was surprisingly rarer as there were many good flakes, yet I got only one and lost one. Gave a number of specimens to Myers.

Jones saw one skink and lost him. Myers partner saw a red racer and lost him. I saw a couple of large skellies.

1929 Monday 15, Apr.

Sunday April 14 (Cont.)
but could not tell whether they were Orcutti or Magister

There were lice (Red) on Crotaphytus and Sauromalus

Returned to camp at 11:30.

About noon walked around the camp for about 20 minutes. Saw only one lizard a small Dipsosaurus which was bagged.

Left camp at 3 P.M.
Narrows 14.5 mi.
Yaqui Well 20.2 at 4 P.M.

Saw only 2 lizards between camp and Yaqui Well. 1 Uta and 1 Whiptail.

No Callys were seen today.

Near the bottom of the Sentenac Canyon the Utas were more in evidence.

1 garter medium D.O.R. Witch Creek.

Count only 75 miles today as it was quite dark at Santee.

Uta microscutata all blue below with brilliant orange throats. Back colors are somewhat different from those at Jacumba.

Bufo punctatus was reported from here the following night by Myers.

1929 Sunday 21, Apr.

Today was a moderately warm clear day; slightly windy in the afternoon.

Went to White Eagle corner via Campo; returned via highway Bostonia and Fletcher Hills. Started at 11:30; returned at 6:10. With family, Jane and Harriet C. 141 miles. Hipass 68 miles.

Camped at 65.8 about 2 miles west of Hipass and hunted here only for about an hour and a half. The granite is soft and does not flake. Nevertheless Xantusias are plentiful under the chunks. Saw 4 under a single piece. They are hard to catch. I got only 3. Also one orcutti. Saw in addition several skellies and utas. Also 1 Bufo b. halophilus under a rock high on a hill. Not near any water. (i.e. 100 yds or more)

While I was hunting Phil caught a large gopher; only live snake seen.

1 gopher L DOR Foot Dulzura grade
1 do S DOR Bingville
1 do S DOR La Posta
1 do S DOR Flynn Spring.
1 Horned toad at Dulzura and 1 halfway up the Potrero grade.

1929 Saturday 27, Apr.

Started for El Centro at 1:30 P.M. with Philip. A cold cloudy day in town. Went out by way of El Cajon Ave and El Cajon. Got somewhat warmer as we proceeded. Not clear until reached the desert. Moderately warm at El Centro. Total miles for the day 167; 91 miles in San Diego County.

Few lizards seen on the road on the way out. Turned up to Painted Gorge to see Walker; road was not bad. Stopped for supper at Als Peace, Plaster City.

In the evening hunted near Heber and got 1 Rana pipiens. Hunted with flash lights in El Centro and then went to the New River but got nothing. Quit at 9PM

Stopped at the Barbara Worth
1 Masticophis lateralis L DOR Alpine
1 Lampropeltis c. californiae L DOR Alpine

Above river the only snakes seen today, alive or dead.

Apr. Sunday 28, 1929

This morning was clear and moderately warm, not hot.

Started for Coyote Wells at 8 AM, and hunted there while waiting for Walker's party. At first there were few lizards out but as it warmed up they became more plentiful. The whiptails seemed to come out first. I got whiptails and callys here (2 each). Lost a good many. Also saw Utas and maybe wislizenii.

Went on to the foot of Mt. Springs grade and hunted here with Walker. Got several Uta mearnsi, 1 chuck, 1 Phyllodactylus (with mites) and saw Utas, Walker saw several Xantusias but I saw none although I turned many stones.

Left Walker at 2 P.M and started for home. Stopped for 1/2 hour at big rocks east of Jacumba and got 4 Uta mearnsi, 2 Uta micro and 1 Uta stans.. Also saw orcutti. Came in via Fletcher Hills.

Total miles today 126; in country 91.

1 deserticolaSDORDixieland
1 LateralisMDORBoulevard
1 AnnectensS DORNewtown
1 OreganusSDORLa Posta
1 OreganusSDORdo (See next page)
1 OreganusSDORViejas
1 LeconteiLDORMurray Dam

Home at 6:45

Apr. Tuesday 30, 1929

Today starting at 1:30 P.M. went out with Chickering and Peckham. A clear mild day. El Cajon Ave, El Cajon, Viejas, Old Viejas Grade, Descanso, Cuyamaca, Julian, Santa Ysabel, Warners Ranch where we stayed all night. 92 miles. Arrived at 5:48 P.M.

Hunted only one place and then for a few moments only this being a North Cuyamaca Peak above the lake. Here 2 Skinks were seen and 1 caught. Quite a few logs were turned over.

1 Annectens Juvenile DOR Grossmont
1 Oreganus Juvenile DOR Alpine*
1 Annectens Juvenile DOR Descanso
1 T.o. hammondii Medium DOR Green Valley
1 Lateralis Large DOR Pine Hills Junction
1 Annectens Juvenile DOR Wynola*

Alligator lizards collected in the road at Oakzanita and Cuyamaca. A few Skellies seen in the road.

In the evening it was quite windy but not cool. Hyla regilla were calling in the creek. Found 2 Bufo b. halophilus hopping in the road but did not collect them.

*Saved specimen.

1929 Wednesday 1, May

Warner's , Mataquay Ranch, Henshaw Dam, Palomar (East to West) Rincon??, Valley Center, Escondido, Vista, Oceanside, San Diego (via Rose Canyon 139 miles.

This day started with a strong east wind which persisted throughout. Moderately cool in the mountains but very hot from Rincon onward. First really hot day of the year. Very dry.

Started for Treanors ranch at 7:40. Had breakfast there. A hard w ind blowing. Nothing seen on the way except 2 snaketracks.

After breakfast climbed quite a ways up the north shoulder of Volcan. Turned over quite a few logs. Nothing seen not even lizards. Hard work. Back at 10:30. Then started for town. Wind still blowing. Did not stop to hunt any place thereafter.

1 ? alive on road hear Henshaw. Probably either gopher or garter but got away in the grass. Was small.

1 OreganusJuvenileDOR.East end Palomar*
1 GarterMedCaughtW. end Palomar
1 Red RacerLargeDOREscondido
1 LateralisLargeDORRose Canyon
1 Gopherdododo

A few Utas seen along the way. 1 Horned toad halfway down the west grade. Didn't stop.

May Thursday 2, 1929

Went to Los Angeles today to address Herpetological Society on "Herpetology for the Amateur". Went alone. Started at 2:10 P.M.; arrived at 6:10. 59.6 miles in S.D. Co.

It was a clear hot day the second hot day of the year. 87 (degrees) in S.D. Clear.

1929 Friday 3, May

Another warm day. Called on Weinberg and got from him an Oreganus caught at Caliente, Kern County.

Then saw Tex Schubach at Long Beach. He had four scutes, 63 atrox, 3 cerastes and 1 molossus. Traded him an exsul for 2 scutes (1 larger) from Victorville; other (smaller) from L.F. Thompson, Peoria, Ariz. Checked some atrox for postnasal, preocular intersecting 34=1, 0=2, 7=3, 0=4. Started home from Long Beach at 12 noon.

May Saturday 4, 1929

Went out with Philip to Borega Hotel. Found it much run down. Evidently this town is for the present a ???. Only a few families living around.

Started at 1:30 P.M. The day was part cloudy and cool all the way to San Felipe Valley where it began to warm up. Was in sharp contrast to the hot days of the middle of the week. Arrived at Borega at 5:30 miles 98.5. Went via Mission Gorge.

Only one or two lizards were seen and snakes were a disappointment. Was very windy from San Felipe down. Punctured crank case of the car on a rock about 3 mi west of the hotel.

1 gopherJuvGrantvilleDOR
1 Banded RacerLTop Mussey G.DOR
1 gopherSmallBallenaCaught on
1 Long NoseLSan FelipeDOR
1 SidewinderLBorego HotelCaught off

Hunted at dark for about one hour (7:30-8:30). Wind had died down somewhat but then started up again. Got one large sidewinder at the roadside. It was pleasantly warm, but too windy. Bed at 9P.M.

1929 Sunday 5, May

At Borega this morning we looked around for a while but saw nothing. It was too windy. Moderately warm. Not uncomfortably hot anytime during the day.

Went home by way of Kane Springs, Mecca, Palm Spring, Banning, Beaumont, Moreno, Elsinore, Fallbrook, Escondido. Total miles today 266.3. Miles in county 75. Miles to be counted (because darkness) 39.

First stop was at Harper's Well for about 1/2 hour. Got 2 Uta stans, 1 Cally and 2 Toads (Probably woodhousii - to be identified later) Woodhousii OK.

Next stop 8 mi. N. of Kane Springs on the highway. 1/2 hour. Stopped here as there were some sandhills near the road and I hoped to find Uma notata. Got 3 Callys and saw one fast cream colored lizard that might have been Uma but can't be sure.

Hunted for an hour around Travertine rock at S.D. - Imp - Riv. Co Junction. Saw many dips but did not get anything.

Very windy east of Banning, dead snakes would have been blown off the road.

Stopped for supper at Escondido at 6:30. From there on it would have been too dark to see anything.

This was a good trip from standpoint of dead specimens but was too long to permit lizard collecting. A surprising number of leafnose and Arizonas.
(For specimen list see under Tuesday April 23rd).

May Monday 6, 1929

(Sunday May 12 Continued)

Hunted for a while in a moderately sandy area 2 mi west of Dixieland and was surprised to get one large Uma. Also saw a Dip and possibly a Cally.

Saw one large Dip near foot of Mt. Spring's grade.

Hunted for a while in the rocks 3 mi east of Jacumba at about 2:30-3:30. Got 3Uta mearnsi and about 7 Uta stans. Also saw Uta micro (tried hard to collect without success) Skellies and Orcuttis. Almost damaged an eye with a yucca.

Went on in at about 3:30. Saw several lizards in the way and one horned toad crossing the road at Jamul at 6:10. Saw several snake tracks and stopped at one but had no luck.

1 gopherSDOR Hipass
1 Banded RacerLDORDulzura
1 Long NoseLDORJamul

Reached home at 7 P.M. Found it hot and humid; more uncomfortable in town than in the back country. Returned via Campo, Spring Valley, La Mesa and El Cajon Ave.. Total miles 225; miles in county 86.

Searl brought in tonight from Laguna 63 garters asst? (1 of which was dead), 1 M gopher, 8 Skinks.

SPalmer

1929 Saturday 11, May

Started for Brawley at 2 P.M. today with the intention of doing some night hunting. With Philip. It was a warm humid day in town; cooler in the back country; not overly hot on the desert. Did no hunting on the way out. A few lizards were seen.

Brake on left read wheel froze on Mt. Spring's grade. Just entering Brawley burned out bearing on right from wheel either due to brake heating or to severe pounding on detour at this point. This finished idea of hunting during the night. Looked around Brawley with spot lights until 9 P.M. in park and at SP depot where the palms were being irrigated but found nothing.

Went out via Market St.. Miles in county 91.7
Total miles to Brawley 142.

May Sunday 12, 1929

Got the car again this morning and started for Kane Springs and beyond at 8:15 to see if snakes were as thick as last week. They weren't. Drove 35 miles up the road and back or about 13 miles beyond Kane Springs.

1 SidewinderSDOR5 mi N. of Kane Springs
1 gopherLDORS of Kane Spr
1 gopherMDORN of West moreland

(Both later were in desert, not cultivated country).

1 P. mcalli found injuredon the road near Kane Spr. Save spec. 2 Callys noted close by here.

1 Dip shot near Kane Spr. Had in his mouth what proved to be the dried skin of a Uma. Couldn't have had it long as it broke away on a slight touch.

Hunted for toads in a small pond north of West moreland which was sufficiently permanent to contain many small fish but found nothing.

Returned to the garage at about 10;40 and had more work done on the bearing which was noisy. Left at 11:40. Figured we would not risk a trip to the sand hills on account of the bering trouble. Didn't want to take any chances.

Returned to El Centro via Holtville. Nothing seen enroute except several squashed toads. Lunched at El Centro. (Continued May 6th)

May Saturday 18, 1929

Started out today with Phil at 1:30 P.M. A clear moderately cool day. Rather warm in El Cajon Valley but cool beyond. A few lizards were seen on the road. First stop in some rocks about a mile or so north of Moretti's (Junction Warners and Henshaw Dam roads). Hunted here for about 1/2 hour. Got 3 Uta stans (1766-8) saw a good many Utas and a few Skellies.

Next stop at a small pond 1/2 way bet.[between] Moretti's and Warner's Hot Springs. Got nothing here. Saw one Hyla regilla.

Arrived at Warner's at 4:30. 71 miles. Reserved room and then went up the road toward Oak Grove 11 miles. In the rocks where I got 2 red rattlers 2 years ago (now an oasis in the burned area) I hunted for half an hour from 5:10 to 5:40. Got one small Boyles King, one large whiptail (1765) and a Uta stans. The snake when first seen was stretched out along the base of a granite rock. He afterwards ate the Uta in the sack. Also saw here but did not collect Orcutti, Skelly and Xantusia. Got a Horned toad on the road at 5:10. Returned to supper at Warners at 6 P.M.

After supper went up the road 1 mile to the big wash. Hunted here 7:30 to 8:30 and had good luck with toads. Found them in dry
(Continued to Wednesday May 15th)

1929 Sunday 19, May

This morning Phil was not feeling well (mumps?) so we decided to return to San Diego. Came in via San Luis Rey Canyon, Amago, Rincin, Pala, Bonsall, El Cajon. Total miles 106.5.

Started at 8AM reached home at 12:30. A clear cool day. A little warm in Rincin and Pala.

Saw many lizards along the way particularly Uta stans and Skellies.

Lost one snake crossing the road about 4 mi. west of Pala. probably garter or banded racer. Was too speedy. A few yards further on was a large banded racer in the center of the road. Had his head up about 10 inches and was surveying the situation. Shot him but was too far away and then lost him down a hole.

Hunted in rocks 4 mi E. of Bonsall. Got one med. Exsul. Had a hard time getting him out of the rocks. Also got 1 Orcutti. Saw Utas and skellies. Did not hunt again and may have missed a snake or two on the way home as of
(Continued on Tuesday May 14)

1929 Tuesday 21, May

Watched a Trimorphodon eat a large Xantusia tonight. Did not see the entire process. When first seen the snake had the lizard by the center of the body with the upper jaw reversed so that it engaged the lizards abdomen. The jaws were widely extended to that the back teeth were effective. The lizard had twisted so that it could not let go. The snake was doing nothing but bite continuously by spasmodic movements of jaw and neck muscles. Movements at about 4 sec. intervals. Did not use body. Kept this up for 7 minutes while observed. I ceased observations here then came back after 10 minutes and found snake swallowing lizard head first. Disturbed him and he dropped lizard. Lizard was quite dead except for spasmodic twitching of tail. Left lizard in cage and it was eaten later.

Worked until midnight tonight pickling speciments. Was greatly helped by Searl and 2 of his boys Marsden and Davis who worked from 7:30 to 11P.M.

Many of the Utah female rattlers contained well developed eggs.

At the roots of the brush. They hide also by going around a branch like a squirrel. They change color notably. The one we caught was dark gray on the branch; cream almost like an albino when in the white sack.

June Sunday 9, 1929

Left Yuma this morning at 7AM. It was clear and comfortably warm as it was all through the desert. Very cool for this time of year. Max. temp today at Yuma was 94. Hottest place we saw was Coyote Well at 3PM which was probably under 100.

1 Desert gopherMDOR 4 mi W of Yuma
1 Sonora occipitalisLDOR10 mi W. of Yuma

Stopped at the sand hills at a point 16.7 miles west of Yuma at 8AM. Hunted until 10AM and then fixed specimens until 10:30 before going on. A fine cooling breeze was blowing; very comfortable. Saw many Umas; got 2 alive and 27 shot. Lost very few. Saw 6 Uta graciosa and got 5 of which one was alive. No other lizards were seen in the sand hills. From the tracks I should judge that the Umas run on their hind legs but I can't see them do it. Too fast. They will take to ground holes where such holes are available which they usually are not. But their usual method of escape is to run behind a brush and dive into the sand or continue on screened by the bush. Difficult to tell which they do except by the tracks. One was noted to jump out of a bush where he probably had an observation post. The large specimens are quite wary and difficult to get.

The Utas hang head downward on bushes principally grease wood. They take refuge in holes
(Continued Friday May 31st)

1929 Wednesday 12, June

Worked tonight putting away pickled specimens.

Tonight watched the Trimorphodon eat another full grown Xantusia henshawi. Again he got ahold with the upper jaw in the abdomen. Again the spasmodic biting, and there was no doubt that the poison was effective as the lizard was quite dead in a short time (10 min?) before swallowing began. The Xantusia was from Sentenac Canyon (Walker).

Tonight noted a small A.e. occidentalis brought in by Walker, taken DOR June 6 in Borego Valley small.

Sent to Bogert
3 Uta mearnsi
2 Cnemidophorus tessellatus tessellatus
2 Uma notata (alive).

Today photographed oreganus from Wenatchee, Wash; Kern Co, Cal (Caliente) and Cannon's scutulatus.

June Wednesday 19, 1929

Drove from Del Monte to San Fransico via Chittenden Pass. Started at 4:30. Arrived at 8:30. Very hot in lower Santa Clara Valley.

1 gopherLDORSargent

1929 Thursday 20, June

After spending morning with Chickering on business attended noon meeting at Berkeley of Am. Soc. Ichth + Herp. to organize a western group or branch.

At U.C. saw a fine series of rattlers all Delta Type from Nevada. Also 3 Lucas and 2 Enyo from the Cape.

In the afternoon borrowed from Slevin 1 Lakeport specimen of Oreganus and 3 Idaho specimens all from Black Creek Canyon 15 mi S. of Boise.

#414 Sept 21 1926
#421-22 Oct 5 1924

Started back to Del Monte via Los Gatos and Santa Cruz at 4:30; arrived at 9:15. A very hot day in Santa Clara Valley. Nothing seen. Miles 129

June Sunday 23, 1929

Started from Santa Maria at 7:40. Very hot today inland. Bothered much by Sunday traffic particularly south of Serra. Travelled via Santa Susana, Santa Ana and Rose Canyon. Miles today 317.5; in county 153.5.

1 ? DOROrcutt. Didn't stop.
1 gopherS.DOR9 mi. N. of Buellton (saved)
1 gopherLDOR5 mi. N. of Buellton
1 gopherLDOR6 mi N. of Elwood (Santa Barbara Co oil field)

Nothing was seen inside county although there were one of two possibilities for which I couldn't stop b/c heavy traffic.

1929 Monday 24, June

Milked rattlers this noon. Got a fairly good lot of venom.

Saw today some Hyla regilla from De Luiz not entered in Walker's list.

Walker told me today of a Boyles King which threw up 3 young Pacific Rattlers; and another which threw up a banded racer larger than itself.

[Note written off to the side]: Wonder if this was true. Probably not

July Friday 5, 1929

Went to Los Angeles on business with GG, Alice and P.A. Bailey. Started at 10 AM. Arrived at 2 P.M. A moderately warm day. 56 miles in county; 120 miles total. Via Rose Canyon and Santa Ana.

1 Long noseLDORLa Costa
1 Boyles KMDORLas Flores

In the evening went to a meeting of the Herp. Society. Supposed to be a specimen night but there was very little to see.

Bogert had the remains of a badly smashed Trimorphodon from Mint Canyon (4 mi. N.W. of Acton).

Roehrig gave me a pickled multicincta from Glendora.

Rowe had 4 Coleonyx from Powerhouse #2 in San Francisquito Canyon. Found on the Powerhouse floor. Gave me one. The bodies are banded instead of spotted like our local form. This ought to be checked up later.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 04/05/2012 01:06 PM
  • SPalmer 04/01/2012 07:38 PM
  • BPOC 11/23/2010 04:21 PM

1929 Saturday 6, July

This morning early I saw Weinberg after a months absence in Arizona. His trip was relatively unsuccessful. Got several very green Crotaphytus collaris. He got altogether 8 snakes; 2 Sonora semiannulata; 2 C. atrox; 3 C. mitchellii; 1 C. tigris. All died enroute home except the sidewinder. He gave me the 2 sonoras not very well preserved. They are from the Huachuca Mts..

He also gave me a Sonora occipitalis and a Phyllorhunchus (latter with a bad tail) said to have been taken between Banning and Cabezon. More likely was east of Cabezon.

Looked at Schubach's staff but he seemed to have little that was not there last time. Nothing interesting so I made no trades.

Started back at 9:30 via Long Beach and Rose Canyon. Nothing seen. Total miles 135; miles in county 56.

July Thursday 11, 1929

Had an interesting talk this morning with Dr. H.C. Kellers U.S.N. just returned from the Phillipines (where he accompanied an eclipse expedition as naturalist) with a large preserved collection of reptiles and other material for the U.S.N.M..

He told me it was necessary to use full strength alcohol in the tropics on reptiles.

With reference to that Sonora occipitalis in the USNM from the "San Diego River" he says he remembers it distinctly but not the exact place as he has forgotten the geography of the county. It was above Old Mission Dam.

July Sunday 21, 1929

Worked today on the Harvard specimens as Loveridge had asked that they be returned at once.

Noted for the first time that the Cedros Island specimens are different from other C. exsul in tail stripes and relation of (between was crossed out and "of" put in it's place) prenasal - first supralabial separation beside (stripes is crossed out here) color, blotches, obsolescense of blotches and size.

Arizona"

Aug. Friday 2, 1929

Photographed specimens this AM.

Recd today from Bogert amongst other lizards a specimen of Phrynosoma douglassii hernandesi that gave birth to 27 young enroute. 26 were alive on arrival. They run with quick short motions. Try to bury themselves in sand rather ineffectually.

Aug. Sunday 4, 1929

Worked today on Ortenburgers (AMNH) Arizona atrox and completed the larger specimens about 28 in all.

Also did some transferring to the new sheets.

Pickled a few specimens.

The kids noted that the young horned toads eat ants naturally. They bob their heads. Bury themselves with fair success.

1929 Monday 5, Aug.

Recd today from Santa Fe

2 Scutes (very light)Bissell, Calif
4 Scutes (very dark)Granite, Ariz
at mile post 47. Check on these not final
1 BlacktailDrake, Ariz

This later seems to be a northern record by a long distance.

Today Walker came in with several good snakes and a fine series of Bufo punctatus from Agua Caliente Spring (but Vallecitos and Carrizo

He also had a worm snake from the same place that I first thought might be Leptotyphlops but it proved not to be. Very unusual color, pink and transparent. Thought it might be an albino, but the eye pigment is there. He had an exsul from well down in the Vallecito which I will preserve.

He told me of an old miner who put aside for him about 15 snakes at Agua Caliente but they were in the sun and all died. Hard luck! ----written off to the side---- "the damn liar"

The Aberdeen Tiger Rattler was seen to issue from a hole at 6:30 P.M.

Aug. Friday 30, 1929

Photographed 1 Molossus and 1 Black Arizona oreganus this morning. No luck with the former.

Milked rattlers this noon.

Today saw a small skink from Deerhorn (Walker) with a bright pink (not blue) tail.

This evening unpacked 23 rattlers from Field Museum and 42 from U.C.. Also 3 from Bogert.

Today put in stock a large Molossus recd yesterday from Santa Fe. Case said Winslow. This is the only specimen to date on which locality data is not ok.

Sept. Sunday 1, 1929

Sick all day today. Nothing done. Walker brought over a couple of specimens.

In the evening had a phone call from Dr. E.H. Taylor, Univ. of Kansas that he had been bitten by a sidewinder the previous night at Yuma. Had taken one dose of antivenin. Had driven all the way from Yuma with one hand. Sounded in bad shape; sent Richmond out with 2 more doses (one of which he gave him). Richmond took him to the Mercy Hospital.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 08/01/2012 12:34 PM
  • Will 06/29/2012 01:20 PM
  • SPalmer 06/09/2012 09:47 AM
  • BPOC 11/23/2010 04:21 PM

1929 Monday 2, Sept.

Saw Taylor for a few moments at Mercy Hospital this morning. He was much better. He was putting a small stick on a sidewinders head to catch him, the stick broke and his hand went forward. He was bitten on the index finger. Only noticed one fang puncture. Opened this but not the other. Got on a tourniquet. Got one dose of antivenin in about 1 hour.

Noted the following in the Taylor collection either dead or alive.

1 ScuteGila Bend
Triseriatus and LepidusHuachucas
PhyllorhynchusYuma
Tigris (a fine Arizona specimen with small head)Sabino Canyon
MolossusAsh Canyon in the Huachucas
Scute (alive)mouth of Ash Canyon
Light MolossusRomero Canyon, Huachucas
Black OreganusMt. Lemmon Catalinas

He had a fine lot of material. Altogether had taken some 50 or more rattlers in New Mexico and Arizona.

Recd a run over M. piceus from Walker near Dulzura.

In the afternoon took Taylor back to his auto camp and talked snakes with him for an hour.

Sept. Thursday 19 1929

Today George in Nat. Hist. Museum told me that one of the Boyles King snakes swallowed another nearly as large. (Captured specimens) Threw it up three days later.

Today received from E.D. McKee as a loan a fine large Grand Canyon Rattler taken on Tanner Trail about three hundred feet below the south rim. This alive. Also two badly mutilated and somewhat decomposed from Desert View Point on the south rim. They are quite different in color although both have distinctive marks. One dark brown like Winslow; the other quite orange colored.

Also received from Chester Lamb from Riveria B.C. a fine series consisting of

3 Mitchellii (M)
13 Lucasensis (2S, 7M, 4L) - 1 large is rather queerly marked
8 Enyo 1L, 7M.

All alive. 1 Lucasensis is in rather poor condition.

Cost 54.00
Transp. 6- La Riveria
Express 3.62
63.62

1929 Tuesday 24, Sept.

Quoting letter from S.P. Jones National Park Service

"C.S. though you would be interested in hearing of a case of cannibalism among horned toads. I kept several in a pen, and, I must admit, I did not feed them regularly. One day I saw a two inch horned toad gulp down a one-inch youngster head first."

Nov. Friday 8, 1929

Started to check confluentus today but instead made a general check of the confluentus-great basin problem from Valle Ariz to Zion Natl Park, Utah across the Grand Canyon. Mapped all specimens and made a general survey. Completed this at 5 P.M.

This evening finished 16 confluentus except for the color notes.

Recd today from Havarahan 1 small Boyles King from Rose Canyon.

Total specimens for vacation to date 108.

Nov. Thursday 28, 1929

---The following is from Nov. Thursday 29, 1929 SP---

Beyond these there remain primary the USNM material of which there is considerable I would like to see particularly

Lucasensis
Exsul (from Lower Calif)
Atrox (from Calif. and Ariz.)
Scutulatus (about 1/2 doz)
Oreganus (from Arizona)
Confluentus (from Mexico and Ariz)

May send for these yet but only after I have returned all now borrowed.

1929 Sunday 1, Dec.

Spent the morning working over the small white confluentus of the Green-Colorado River Valley. Made final comparisons. Selected a type specimen (Field 923) from Grand Junction.

Afternoon at MKs.

In the evening worked on mapping the Calif. tigris and adjacent Great Basin and Mitchellii specimens. Have a few more to check - awaiting geological survey sheets now on order to do this. Will then be able to unite up three new subspecies or four; that is after making a visual inspection of border material.

1929 Friday 13, Dec.

Rode out on Otay Mesa and to Tui Juana to look at lines. 25 miles in snake territory. Nothing seen. A clear warm day; no rain since early Sept.

Worked all day on confluentus paper.

1929 Saturday 21, Dec.

Spent the past week on a vacation working up paper on lutosus, decolor, stephensi, and abyssus.

Practically finished first draft today. From now on will take lots of work to round it into shape.

California King snake

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
